<pre><code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; arr = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(); ArrayList&lt;Double&gt; doub = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();         arr.add(5);         arr.add(6);         arr.add(7);         doub.add(6.5);         doub.add(8.5);         doub.add(7.5);         calc_test(arr);         calc_test(doub);  public static void calc_test(List&lt;Number&gt; list) {         for (Number obj : list) {             System.out.println(obj + "");         }     } </code></pre>  <p>I know this is an error in java and can be corrected by adding <code>? extends Number</code> in the function parameter, but why does the normal way not work? After all double and integer are a type of number and a list of those types should still be a type of number, so why is that an error?</p>